Hi MOOSE community,
I opened a similar discussion #24312 a while ago. But since at that time I was still able to build and run MOOSE without all the python packages, I closed the question as resolved.

Makefile in ~/projects/moose/framework/contrib/hit
CXX ?= g++
UNAME := $(shell uname)

pyconfig := python3-config
ifeq (, $(shell which $(pyconfig) 2>/dev/null))
	pyconfig := python-config
endif
cython := cython3
ifeq (, $(shell which $(cython) 2>/dev/null))
	cython := 'cython -3'
endif

ifeq ($(UNAME), Darwin)
	DYNAMIC_LOOKUP := -undefined dynamic_lookup
else
	DYNAMIC_LOOKUP :=
endif

$(info Building hit for python with $(pyconfig))

PYTHONPREFIX ?= `$(pyconfig) --prefix`
PYTHONCFLAGS ?= `$(pyconfig) --cflags`
HITCPP := hit.cpp

WASP_DIR           ?= $(abspath ../wasp/install)

# find the wasp libraries
lib_suffix := so
ifeq ($(shell uname -s),Darwin)
	lib_suffix := dylib
	wasp_LIBS         := $(shell find -E $(WASP_DIR)/lib -regex ".*/lib[a-z]+.$(lib_suffix)")
else
	wasp_LIBS         := $(wildcard $(WASP_DIR)/lib/libwasp*$(lib_suffix))
endif
wasp_LIBS         := $(notdir $(wasp_LIBS))
wasp_LIBS         := $(patsubst %.$(lib_suffix),%,$(wasp_LIBS))
wasp_LIBS         := $(patsubst lib%,-l%,$(wasp_LIBS))
ifeq ($(wasp_LIBS),)
  $(error WASP does not seem to be available. Make sure to either run scripts/update_and_rebuild_wasp.sh in your MOOSE directory, or set WASP_DIR to a valid WASP install)
endif

wasp_CXXFLAGS  += -I$(WASP_DIR)/include
wasp_LDFLAGS   += -Wl,-rpath,$(WASP_DIR)/lib -L$(WASP_DIR)/lib $(wasp_LIBS)

hit: main.cc parse.cc lex.cc braceexpr.cc braceexpr.h lex.h parse.h
	$(CXX) -std=c++17 $(wasp_CXXFLAGS) -g $(CXXFLAGS) $< parse.cc lex.cc braceexpr.cc -o $@ $(wasp_LDFLAGS)

bindings: hit.so

hit.so: parse.cc lex.cc braceexpr.cc
	$(CXX) -std=c++17 $(wasp_CXXFLAGS) -w -fPIC -lstdc++ -shared -L$(PYTHONPREFIX)/lib $(PYTHONCFLAGS) $(DYNAMIC_LOOKUP) $^ $(HITCPP) -o $@ $(wasp_LDFLAGS)

$(HITCPP): hit.pyx chit.pxd
	$(cython) -o $@ --cplus $<

.PRECIOUS: $(HITCPP)

.PHONY: clean bindings

clean:
	rm -f hit hit.so

node.bodyText:
I am trying to solve the mass conservation equation in the current configuration where the background mesh is moving. In the absence of boundary conditions, the weak form of my equation is
$\psi \frac{\partial \rho}{\partial t } - \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial x_i} \rho \dot{x}_i = 0$
which I have implemented into MOOSE and have verified that the Jacobians are all correct. I'm stretching the mesh to be twice the volume by moving the boundaries and using diffusion kernels to propagate into the inside of the mesh so I would anticipate that the density would drop by a half but what is happening is that each of the kernels in isolation is going to zero so that the density assumes a non-constant shape. To be more clear, for a 1D element of length 1 being stretched at a rate of 1 / time at time = 1
For the time derivative:

But I could swap in $\rho = 0.5$ and $\frac{\partial \rho}{\partial t} = \pm 0.5$ and that would also solve the expression and would be the physical answer I would expect. How do I prevent this behavior?

I think that the answer may be that I'm not including all of the terms from the balance of mass. There is a boundary term that I think needs to be included given the form that I've chosen.
$\frac{D}{Dt} \int_{\mathcal{B}} \rho dv = 0$
$\int_{\mathcal{B}_0} \frac{D}{Dt}\left(\rho J\right) dV = 0$
$\rightarrow \frac{\partial \rho}{\partial t} + \frac{\partial \rho}{\partial x_i}\dot{x}_i + \rho \frac{\partial \dot{x}_i}{\partial x_i} = \frac{\partial \rho}{\partial t} + \frac{\partial}{\partial x_i} \left(\rho \dot{x}_i\right) = 0$
So the weak form is
$\psi \frac{\partial \rho}{\partial t} + \frac{\partial}{\partial x_i} \left(\psi \rho \dot{x}_i\right) - \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial x_i} \rho \dot{x}_i = 0$
So I was missing the middle term. I'll update this after I get things working in MOOSE.

node.title: Using old value of AD variable in ADMaterial
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I need to use the current and the old value of an AD variable (void_fraction) in ADMaterial, so I just define:
  _void_fraction(adCoupledValue("void_fraction")),
  _void_fraction_old(coupledValueOld("void_fraction")),

I would like to know if there is something wrong in ADMaterial since the _void_fraction_old is not AD type. I think adCoupledValueOld is  better but there is no such type. Could anyone kindly tell me? Thanks!

Hello
There are no 'old' dofs in the current equation system so we do not need to track the dependency of the material properties with regards to old dofs. Hence why we dont use AD for old and older properties. AD is only for the derivatives with regards to current DOFs
Guillaume
Because "void_fraction" is a variable, not a material property. I need to get the old value of this AD variable, so I use coupledValueOld.

Should I define an AD material property (_void_property), and let _void_property[_qp] = _void_fraction[_qp]. Then I get the old value using _void_property(getADMaterialPropertyOld<Real>(void_fraction))?

coupledValueOld is fine. We dont need AD for old.

Should I define an AD material property (_void_property), and let _void_property[_qp] = _void_fraction[_qp]. Then I get the old value using _void_property(getADMaterialPropertyOld(void_fraction))?

this is not going to do anything good. It will make it look AD but the derivatives will still be 0 because you're looking at the old material property now
I got it, thanks!
